Classification.Comment: A confirmed de novo heterozygous duplication of 4p16.3-p11 encompassing 185 genes (https://genescout.omim.org/) was identified by exome sequencing in one individual with a neurodevelopmental disorder and agenesis of corpus callosum ([GRCh38] chr4:1_49062177x3). These breakpoints have been estimated by exome sequencing only and therefore may not reflect the true breakpoints. The patient phenotype is nonspecific, but is consistent with cases described in the literature and/or published databases with overlapping variants. There are no known triplosensitive genes contained within the duplicated region, but a triplosensitivity predictor suggests that multiple genes (PHOX2B, CTBP1, NKX1-1, HTT, RBPJ, PDS5A, RGS12) included in this duplication are triplosensitive (https://www.deciphergenomics.org/). In summary, the 4p16.3-p11 duplication meets criteria to be classified as pathogenic. The ACMG/ClinGen evidence codes and points used in this curation are as follows: 1: 0 points, 2: 0 points, 3: 0.90 points, 4-5: 0.15 points; Total: 1.05 points; Riggs 2020 (PMID: 31690835).
